In the before-times, Cataldo's was among the least flashy places to eat on this stretch of Vanderbilt Ave. It's also one of the best. It is a perfect red-sauce joint, cozy, with delicious food, great prices and big portions, bottles of wine (good wine!) under $30, and serious pizza. It's also a great place to stop in for a to-go chicken parm hero on your way to the park.  And, importantly: they deliver! Call them, they're fast, food is packaged well and hot on arrival. The chicken francese is as ethereal as it is in the restaurant.

What is this place? How are they in business? Mom is eating her dinner at a table in the completely empty dining room upon arrival. Son/cook is on a chair watching TV in the back. Dad is asleep ( no lie ) on a chair by the toilet. Food is tasteless & dreadful. The only other sound is the radio playing from the kitchen, no music playing front of house. Candles got lit, over an hour after it was dark outside yet no lights were dimmed inside so it was as bright as day. Zero atmosphere or personality from the souls inside. It seems this family have given up on everything. Gordon Ramsey would have an absolute field day with these guys on an episode of kitchen nightmares. It’s a shame because the place has the potential to be great but by the looks of it, it’s only a matter of time before it shuts its doors permanently.

Out of all the quaint and delish options on Vanderbilt Ave. come inside and feel like family. It’s the Italian touch in the heart of Prospect Heights. If you come with a group on a casual weekday or weeknight, the opportunity is yours if you want to have the waitress sit down and tell stories around the table.  Don’t rush with your food, enjoy the pastas or brunch options. I’m a fan of the Fettuccini Alfredo. Have a cappuccino and people watch, or have great convos while Italian cuisines are yours for the taking.

This is truly an amazing place. Incredible Italian Food. Homemade taste like you were eating at your family's home. Excellent marinara sauce (perfect in my opinion). Sal and Russ & family really know their stuff and they treat everyone that walks in like family. They have wood fired brick oven pizza that is perfect. Usually we get the Pugliese (broccoli rabe and sausage) which is exactly what we got this time (lol). They have a lot of great pizza but that's my favorite. Fried calamari is always incredible. We also had chicken parm and penne alla vodka, and salmon with broccoli. I finished off with one of their daily specials Rigatoni Norma (rigatoni with fried eggplant and ricotta cheese). Wow it was so good i came again the same week for the same dish (and the Pugliese pizza and Fried calamari LOL).  Finished off with an expresso with sambuca. I have know Sal for many years and he really knows his stuff. Pasta always al dente (little firm, which is the only way you should eat pasta), marinara sauce is always perfect (just like when mom makes it), as is everything they make there. Also, don't forget they make the best Italian sandwiches. My favorite is the mixed seafood (fried shrimp & calamari) with marinara sauce (i like it spicy so i add crushed red pepper). Good size portions and reasonable pricing make this the go to spot in the area. Try for yourself you won't be disappointed. Highly recommend. Buon Appetito!
